earth as a process, condition, and space tied to planetary exchanges of energy and matter. Aided by the US militarization of the Arctic during the Cold War, the engineering view of frozen earth as an obstacle to construction became dominant. The Life of Permafrost tells the fascinating story of how permafrost came to acquire life as Russian and Soviet scientists studied, named, and defined it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFrozen ground-Research. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aArctic.  aCold War.  aEurasia.  aRussia.  aSiberia.  aSoviet Union.  aenvironment.  afrozen earth.  afrozen ground.  ahistory of Soviet science.  ahistory of geography.  ahistory.  apermafrost science.  apermafrost.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751424240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487514242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487514242.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles